ek. He=E2=80=99s arriving into what=E2=80=99s known in the high-end corpora=
te communications world as=E2=80=A6 <i>hmm, what=E2=80=99s the word</i>=E2=
=80=94right, yes, a =E2=80=9Cshitshow.=E2=80=9D<br/> <br/>Forget Zaslav=E2=
=80=99s various P.R. flubs. Since the Warner Discovery transaction closed t=
o much fanfare in April 2022, his company has now lost more than two-thirds=
 of its value. Zaz has whittled its debt down to under $40 billion, but his=
 linear television business is nose-diving faster than his streaming busine=
ss is growing. He just laid off another 1,000 employees. He=E2=80=99s got u=
ntil Monday to scramble to match Amazon=E2=80=99s $1.8 billion per year dea=
l for a small package of NBA games=E2=80=94a deal that WBD probably can=E2=
=80=99t afford
and that NBA commissioner <b>Adam Silver</b> specifically structured to <i>=
exclude</i> the league=E2=80=99s longtime partner. His two summer movies (<=
i>Furiosa</i> and <i>Horizon</i>) both flopped in theaters, one so badly th=
at its sequel had to be pulled from release. And even HBO, the prestige jew=
el of the company, was beaten in yesterday=E2=80=99s Emmy nominations not j=
ust by Netflix but FX, which only a few years ago was written off as a casu=
alty of the streaming wars.   <br/> <br/>At the same time, Zaslav and his S=
un Valley neckerchief have been given nearly $350 million in compensation s=
ince 2021. Of course, a lot of those awards were in stock, which obviously =
has not translated to cash. But the fact that, amid such massive value dest=
ruction, Zaslav=E2=80=99s pay metric was changed to reward free cash flow, =
rather than stock performance, has made a mockery of the supposed sharehold=
er-driven, <i>you-win-I-win</i> rationale for exorbitant executive comp.  <=
br/> <br/>But change may be
afoot. The first sign came in a dagger of an analyst report on Tuesday from=
 <b>Jessica Reif Ehrlich</b> and the BofA Securities team, which bluntly st=
ated that the current Warner Discovery strategy =E2=80=9Cis not working=E2=
=80=9D and posited that =E2=80=9Cexploring strategic alternatives such as a=
sset sales, restructuring and/or mergers would create more shareholder valu=
e vs. the status quo.=E2=80=9D The report then laid out six possible scenar=
ios for Zaz: 1) sell the company; 2) sell some assets; 3) merge, preferably=
 with the home of a broadcast network; 4) do a streaming merger or joint ve=
nture; 5) stay the course; or 6) spin off the linear assets (and the debt) =
into a separate company.<br/> <br/>Of these, the report argued, the spinoff=
 might make sense. And the market seemed to agree=E2=80=94or, rather, it be=
lieves some kind of action is coming, because the Warner Discovery stock sh=
ot up 8 percent. Then, a day later, almost as if Zaz had read the note and =
then called the <i>Financial Times</i> to
declare that <i>Yeah, of course we=E2=80=99re considering all that</i>, the=
<i> FT</i> <a href=3D"https://email.puck.news/e/c/eyJlbWFpbF9pZCI6ImRnVDJ4Z=
